'''Ketevan Lomtatidze''' (Georgian: ქეთევან ლომთათიძე; 1911–2007) was a Georgian linguist ([[Caucasiology|Caucasiologist]]), specialist in [[Kartvelian studies|Kartvelian]] and [[Abkhaz language|Abkhaz]] studies. == Life == In 1931, she graduated from the department of philology of the Tbilisi State University, specializing in [[Abkhaz language|Abkhaz]] and [[Abaza language]]. Some authors regard her as the greatest researcher of these two languages.<ref>*[http://abkhazology.files.wordpress.com/2011/02/qetevan4.pdf Кетеван Ломтатидзе - 100]</ref>
She was the first woman to acquire a Doctor of Science degree in Georgia (1945). From 1953 to 1963 and from 1975 to 1987 she worked as the Director of the Institute of Linguistics of the Academy of Sciences of the Georgian SSR.
In 1984 she was awarded the ''Dmitry Gulia State Prize of Abkhazia''.
Throughout her academic career, she published around 400 works (including 8 books) in Georgian, Abkhaz, Russian, English and German language.
